{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2579"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.84,0.01,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107504"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2579"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39919"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to his general practitioner for review. He reports a new onset headache that is pulsatile in nature, located over the left frontotemporal region and it has not responded to simple analgesia. This pain started yesterday. He has also felt feverish and off his food since yesterday afternoon. On examination, he looks unwell, he is febrile at 38.0\u00b0C but other vitals are normal. On cranial nerve exam, he reports some diplopia using his left eye and tenderness over his left scalp as well as left masseter muscle.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments is most important to initiate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV ceftriaxone","IV methylprednisolone","IV acetaminophen","IV aspirin","IV sumatriptan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question focusses on acute neurological presentations and the associated initial treatment. In an older patient (\u0026gt;50) with a new headache, it is important to rule out serious causes before labelling it as a primary headache. A unilateral headache focussed around the temporal region, with eye changes and tenderness to palpation are all red flags for \u003Cstrong\u003Egiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E (GCA) (sometimes referred to as temporal arteritis). This is an autoimmune medium/large vessel vasculitis that most commonly affects the superficial temporal artery. Key presentation symptoms include headache, jaw pain/claudication, visual changes including blindness, scalp tenderness and some systemic features such as low grade fever, neuropathies or weight loss. It is a clinical diagnosis requiring 3 out of 5 criteria:\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge \u0026gt;50\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew headache\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbnormal temporal artery: tenderness or decreased palpation\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR \u0026gt;50\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbnormal biopsy: vasculitis with giant cell granulomatous infiltration\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is critical to note that treatment can be initiated prior to a definitive diagnosis from an artery biopsy. Initial treatment involves high-dose prednisolone (50-60mg daily) for a number of weeks before beginning to wean the dose whilst assessing for any return of symptoms. This is usually oral prednisolone, though IV methylprednisolone may be used if visual or neurological symptoms are presen\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP may be elevated as the ESR can be normal initially. An elevated platelet count (thrombocytosis) may also be found. Normal levels of inflammatory markers or platelet count does not rule out the diagnosis of GCA, however.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther differentials to consider where \u003Cstrong\u003Emeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E (IV ceftriaxone being part of the treatment), an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute intracranial bleed\u003C/strong\u003E (where IV acetaminophen may be used for pain management), an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute stroke\u003C/strong\u003E (where IV aspirin may be used in certain cases) or or \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute migraine\u003C/strong\u003E (where a triptan may be used but commonly this is a preventative medication). These are all less likely differentials in the above scenario.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Consider the possibility of giant cell arteritis (GCA) in an elderly patient presenting with new temporal headache, especially if visual disturbance is present.","Immediate initiation of high-dose corticosteroids is crucial in suspected giant cell arteritis to prevent irreversible vision loss."],"references":["Smith JH, Swanson JW. Giant cell arteritis. Headache. 2014 Sep;54(8):1273-89. doi: 10.1111/head.12425. Epub 2014 Jul 18. PMID: 25041449. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25041449/","Younger DS. Giant Cell Arteritis. Neurol Clin. 2019 May;37(2):335-344. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2019.01.008. Epub 2019 Mar 16. PMID: 30952412. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30952412/","Chan FLY, Lester S, Whittle SL, Hill CL. The utility of ESR, CRP and platelets in the diagnosis of GCA. BMC Rheumatol. 2019 Apr 10;3:14. doi: 10.1186/s41927-019-0061-z. PMID: 31008443; PMCID: PMC6456976. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31008443/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2579"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89984"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T15:38:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T15:39:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2579"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student a